•
Had a handful of people ask about my router table setup.
I got this a couple years ago when I thought I would be using it more on the road/on-site. 
Since then it stays in the shop most of the time so I built this handy cart. It’s on leveling casters and I’m able to store my other trim routers and router bits. 👌🏽

Meet the Advisory Board - Alma @pinksoulstudios 

Pink Soul translates from Spanish to Alma Rosa - her brand is literally her name and her heritage, and both like her creativity have been with her since she was born.
Like many woodworkers, Alma’s first influences came from her family. Her grandfather was an original DIYer, and her mother provided a super creative effect on her as well. Alma bought her first house in Detroit when she was 24, and because she couldn’t afford much at the time, she started building things as she needed them. 
Soon after, Alma started making things for her family and friends and slightly further afield. She moved away from woodworking for several years as her interest in engines grew, especially those for smaller motorcycles and vintage scooters. However, after her son was born and they moved to Chicago, she wanted to make his toys and furniture, and the woodworking passion reignited.
In the last few years Alma has added an Avid CNC to her shop.  And that’s enabled her to create products for her web store as well as her etsy store.  Along with being able to switch into production mode with her CNC she’s been able to collaborate and assist other makers with templates, jigs and custom woodwork. 💘

#workbenchcon #wbcbranchingout
